What Aristotle wrote is most true, that certainty is not to be found in morals as it is in mathematics: of which the reason is this, that mathematios separate the forms of things altogether from matter: and that the forms are of such a nature that there is nothing intermediate between two of them3 as between a straight line and a curve there is no medium. But in moral matters, circum- stances, even the least, often vary the matter3 and the forms that are treated have often intermediate degrees, of such latitude that the case sometimes approaches nearer to the one extreme, sometimes to the other.
